unchanged and are included with the distribution.
The archive must contain the following files:

       CEDPatch_1.0/
               CEDPatch
               CEDPatch.guide
               CEDPatch.guide.info
               CEDPatch.info
       CEDPatch_1.0.info

@ENDNODE


@NODE 2. "Requirements"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Kickstart 2.04 (V37) or better and CygnusEd V3.5.

@ENDNODE


@NODE 3. "Installation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
  1. Put CEDPatch it in any drawer you like and put the line
     '<path>/CEDPatch >NIL:' in S:User-Startup (<path> being the
     path to the drawer you chose).

 or

  2.  Drop CEDPatch in your WBStartup drawer.

CEDPatch simply installes the patch and terminates immediately, so
there is no need for using 'run' or even the standard tooltype
'DONOTWAIT'!

See also @{" Arguments " LINK 6.}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 4. "Introduction"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
CygnusEd is a great editor. However, the v3.5 release seems to behind in
a few areas. Although the v3.5 was released quite a bit after Kickstart
2.x, it still looks like a program belonging to the Kickstart 1.x age.
Although v3.5 is aware of KS2.x+ features such as pubscreen, it still
insists on using the fixed-width System Default Font as it's screen font
and the topaz font as it's menu font. Furthermore, the menus has a
non-standard look that in no way resembles the recommendations in the
"Amiga User Interface Style Guide" (AUISG) book.

If these flaws has ever bothered you then CEDPatch is what you need.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 5. "Details"

Details
~~~~~~~
CEDPatch can improve CED v3.5's look quite a bit. This is a
list of what is achieved:

 - Use any font as screen font. Any fixed-width font or proportional
   fonts will do.

 - The menus use the screen font. You are no longer forced to look
   at the old topaz font.

 - The menus are re-layoutet to look more KS2.x+ alike. In detail:

    - The menu "Environment", which formerly covered three menus,
      has been split into three menus, each with it's own name.
      Now called "Global", "File" and "View" respectively.
      Therefor, the unselectable in-menu titles in those three menus
      ("Global Settings", "File Settings" and "View Settings") has
      been removed.

    - Menu items with subitems are now inverted the normal way
      instead of being highlighted by a box being drawn around
      them.

    - Menu items with special hotkeys has had their hotkeys shortened a bit:

        "Spawn new CED      Ctrl+Esc"        -> "Spawn new CED        c esc"
        "Activate next CED  Ctrl+n"          -> "Ativate next CED       c n"

        "Delete word        Ctrl+Del"        -> "Delete word          c del"
        "Undelete word      Ctrl+Alt+Del"    -> "Undelete word      c a del"
        "Bck Spc word       Ctrl+BckSpc"     -> "Bck Spc word"     c bckspc"
        "UnBck Spc word     Ctrl+Alt+BckSpc" -> "UnBck Spc word  c a bckspc"

    - The 'Move' menu has had it's in-menu titles removed and hotkeys
      added to the items themselves. The menu has been transformed
      like this:

        "Jump to line..."                    -> "Jump to line..."
        "Jump to auto-mark"                  -> "Jump to auto-mark"
        "Jump to byte..."                    -> "Jump to byte..."
        "Shift+Cursor keys"                  ->
        "   Beg of screen"                   -> "Beg of screen      s up"
        "   End of screen"                   -> "End of screen    s down"
        "   Beg of line"                     -> "Beg of line      s left"
        "   End of line"                     -> "End of line     s right"
        "Alt+Cursor keys"                    ->
        "   Up 12 lines"                     -> "Up 12 lines        a up"
        "   Down 12 lines"                   -> "Down 12 lines    a down"
        "   Left 12 chars"                   -> "Left 12 chars    a left"
        "   Right 12 chars"                  -> "Right 12 chars  a right"
        "Ctrl+Cursor keys"                   ->
        "   Beg of file"                     -> "Beg of file        c up"
        "   End of file"                     -> "End of file      c down"
        "   Prev word"                       -> "Prev word        c left"
        "   Next word"                       -> "Next word       c right"

@ENDNODE

@NODE 6. "Arguments"

Arguments
~~~~~~~~~
CEDPatch can be started from shell as well as from Workbench and takes
the same arguments. The '.info' file is used as a config file and the
tooltypes in it is read even if CEDPatch is started from shell !
Any commandline argument takes precedence over a similar specified
in the '.info' file. I.e. if you specify 'FONT=topaz/11' in the '.info'
file and the start CEDPatch from shell with 'FONT=topaz/9' then it is
the latter which is used. But if you start CEDPatch from shell without
specifying a value for FONT on the commandline, then the 'FONT=topaz/11'
from the '.info' file is used.

The patch can be removed by simply running CEDPatch a second time. If run
from a shell CEDPatch will print a little message indicating whether it
is being installed or removed.

The argument template is this:

  FONT/K,WBFONT/S


  FONT/K         - The font to be used as the screen font when CED opens
                   it's own screen. The System Default font, which is
                   fixed-width, will be used if neither FONT nor WBFONT
                   is specified.

                   Example:

                     Workbench: FONT=topaz/11

                     Shell:     FONT=topaz/11
                                FONT topaz/11

  WBFONT/S       - The font currently specified as the screen font for
                   the Workbench screen will also be used as CED's
                   screen font. See also FONT above.

                   Example:

                     Workbench: WBFONT

                     Shell:     WBFONT

NOTE: If you specify both a FONT and WBFONT at the same time then FONT
      is ignored

@ENDNODE

